insert into quests (day_number, title, subtitle, description, tier, xp_value, is_boss) values
(1, 'Hello, World!', 'Start here', 'Python is an interpreted language, which means it reads and executes code line by line. That order matters, because what you write first can affect what happens next. Today we start with print, the command that tells Python to show text on the screen. At first it feels simple, but print is one of the most useful tools in programming because it lets you confirm what a program is doing, what an object contains, or whether a script finished successfully. If something completes, you might print Finished. If it does not, you might print Unfinished. Your task is to write a program that prints Hello World.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(2, 'Print with purpose', 'Show output clearly', 'Printing is more than making text appear. It is how you explain state, verify results, and trace what your program is thinking. In this lesson, practice using print to display different messages so you understand how output can help both users and programmers.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(3, 'Variables', 'Store values', 'Variables let Python remember information so you do not have to repeat it. A variable is a name attached to a value, and that makes programs easier to read, change, and reuse. In this quest, store a few values and use them in more than one place so you can see why variables are essential.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(4, 'Input basics', 'Talk to the user', 'Programs become more useful when they can respond to a real person. The input function pauses and waits for the user to type something, then hands that text back to your code. Today you will learn how input turns a static script into an interactive conversation.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(5, 'Numbers and math', 'Work with values', 'Python treats numbers as data that can be calculated, compared, and reused. This quest explains why numeric values are different from text and how that difference allows you to add, subtract, and build logic such as scores, counters, and totals.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(6, 'Strings', 'Text matters', 'Strings are how Python stores words, names, messages, and dialogue. Understanding strings helps you build menus, prompts, and game text. You will practice combining and shaping text so you can see how messages are constructed from pieces.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(7, 'Mini challenge 1', 'First checkpoint', 'The first checkpoint is about combining what you have learned so far. Use print, input, and variables together to create a tiny interactive script. The goal is not just to make it run, but to understand how each part supports the others.', 'boss', 100, true),
(8, 'Lists', 'Store many items', 'Lists are useful when one value is not enough. If you need to keep track of inventory, steps, names, or options, a list gives you a tidy way to group them. This lesson shows why lists are the right tool when you need several related values together.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(9, 'If statements', 'Make choices', 'Conditionals give your program decision-making power. They let code follow different paths depending on what is true or false. In this quest, you will write simple if statements so you can understand how programs choose what to do next.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(10, 'Loops', 'Repeat with control', 'Loops exist so you do not have to write the same instruction over and over. They are especially useful when you want a message, action, or calculation to happen multiple times. Today you will practice repetition and see how loops reduce duplication.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(11, 'While loops', 'Keep going until done', 'A while loop keeps running until a condition changes. That makes it ideal for tasks where you do not know the exact number of repetitions ahead of time. This quest helps you understand why loops are often built around a stop condition.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(12, 'Dictionaries', 'Label your data', 'Dictionaries pair keys with values, which makes them great for structured information. Instead of asking, "What index is this?", you can ask, "What is the value for this name?". This lesson helps you see why labels make programs easier to understand.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(13, 'Functions', 'Reuse behavior', 'Functions bundle a set of steps into a named unit so you can run them whenever you need them. They improve organization, reduce repetition, and make code easier to test. In this quest, you will learn why functions are one of the most important tools in programming.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(14, 'Mini challenge 2', 'Second checkpoint', 'This checkpoint asks you to combine logic, input, and output into a slightly bigger script. Think about why each line is there and how the program changes based on the user’s input.', 'boss', 100, true),
(15, 'Debugging', 'Read the clues', 'Errors are not just problems; they are clues. Debugging is the process of using those clues to figure out what went wrong and why. This quest teaches you how to read errors carefully instead of guessing.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(16, 'Lists in depth', 'Change collections', 'Now that you have seen lists, this lesson goes further. Practice adding, removing, and looping through items so you understand how Python manages collections of values.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(17, 'String methods', 'Shape text', 'Programs often need to clean, split, or transform text before using it. String methods help you do that. This quest shows why text processing matters in real applications.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(18, 'Functions with inputs', 'Pass values in', 'Functions become even more useful when they accept information and return a result. That is how you build flexible tools instead of one-off scripts. This lesson focuses on why input and output make functions powerful.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(19, 'Files', 'Remember later', 'Files allow programs to store information after they close. Without files, every run would start from zero. This quest explains why saving data matters for progress, settings, and long-lived information.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(20, 'Try and except', 'Handle mistakes safely', 'Sometimes code fails, and that is normal. Try and except lets you handle a failure without crashing the whole program. This lesson helps you understand the value of graceful error handling.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(21, 'Mini challenge 3', 'Third checkpoint', 'Use what you know to build a small quiz or scoring script. The purpose of this checkpoint is to make sure the pieces work together and that you understand how the program flows.', 'boss', 100, true),
(22, 'Modules', 'Use existing tools', 'Modules let you borrow code that already exists. This saves time and keeps your own code focused on the problem you are solving. Today you will import something useful and see why code reuse matters beyond your own file.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(23, 'Planning a project', 'Break it apart', 'Big projects feel easier when they are broken into small tasks. Planning helps you decide what to build first and what can wait. This quest teaches you how to think like a builder before you start typing.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(24, 'Classes basics', 'Model things', 'Classes let you describe objects with data and behavior. They are the foundation for modeling characters, items, enemies, and other game elements. This lesson explains why object-oriented thinking is useful in larger programs.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(25, 'Capstone helpers', 'Put pieces together', 'This quest asks you to combine multiple skills in a small project. The point is to see how earlier lessons support a real program and why planning and structure matter.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(26, 'Review day', 'Strengthen understanding', 'Review is where ideas become habits. Revisit the concepts that felt hardest and explain them in your own words. That reflection is what turns memorized syntax into real understanding.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(27, 'Final mini project', 'Fourth checkpoint', 'Build a small finished app using the skills you have learned. The focus is not only on making it work, but on understanding why the code is organized the way it is.', 'boss', 100, true),
(28, 'Celebrate and continue', 'You are ready', 'This final quest is a reflection on everything you learned. By now you should understand the basics of Python, the purpose behind each tool, and how to keep building from here.', 'beginner', 25, false)
